ractice -- t13 Perempuan mengkaji seni: Gender, activism and Indonesian visual arts -- t14 Feminist intervention in cultural activism -- t15 Male caregiver protagonists on the silver screen: A middle-class biased shift of ideal masculinity -- tIndex -- tINDONESIA UPDATE SERIES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past 20 years, gender relations and the expression of power and authority between men and women in Indonesia have been shaped by the forces of reformasi, decentralisation, a reassertion of central power, and economic transitions. These changes have given rise to policy reform, an increase in women’s political representation, and new expressions of diverse gender identities. But to what extent has the 'gender order' of the New Order, where women’s role as a mother was the basis of citizenship, been challenged or just found new articulations? What shape do contemporary contestations to gendered power take? The chapters in this volume bring gender to the centre stage and provide reflections on the political, economic, social, and cultural progress and barriers in achieving gender equality and diversity in Indonesia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aWomen's Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAndjaringtyas Adhi, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBexley, Angie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBexley, Angie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBudianto, Vania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirgantoro, Wulan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDong, Sarah Xue, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEliyanah, Evi, eco